(43, 18, 33, 43, 18, 37, 37, NULL, 'Connection of Kingship Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of kingship as Pilate questions Jesus about being ''a king.'' Both passages emphasize Jesus'' identity and purpose in relation to truth and kingship.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 35, 15, 4, 12, 12, 'thine own nation', 'Connection of Jewish Accusation', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Jews in delivering accusations. In John, Pilate notes that ''thine own nation'' delivered Jesus, while Ezra mentions the Jews as ''rebellious'' in their actions. This connection highlights the theme of Jewish opposition in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 35, 16, 4, 2, 2, 'Am I a Jew?', 'Jewish Identity and Struggle', 'This connection highlights the perception of Jews as ''feeble'' in Nehemiah and Pilate''s dismissal of Jesus'' identity as a Jew. Both passages emphasize the challenges faced by the Jewish people in the face of external opposition.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 35, 43, 18, 28, 28, NULL, 'Judgment and Defilement Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the tension between the Jewish leaders and Pilate regarding Jesus'' fate. The mention of the judgment hall in John 18:28 and Pilate''s inquiry about what Jesus has done in John 18:35 reflects the conflict surrounding the Passover and the leaders'' desire to avoid defilement.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 35, 43, 19, 6, 6, NULL, 'Pilate''s Judgment on Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s role in the trial of Jesus. In John 18:35, Pilate questions what Jesus has done, while in John 19:6, he declares he finds no fault in him, highlighting the tension between his judgment and the demands of the chief priests.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 35, 44, 3, 13, 13, 'delivered thee unto me', 'Delivery of Jesus to Pilate', 'Both passages emphasize the act of delivering Jesus to Pilate. In John, Pilate notes that ''thine own nation and the chief priests have delivered thee unto me,'' while Acts states that ''whom ye delivered up'' in reference to Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 35, 44, 18, 14, 16, 'what hast thou done?', 'Judgment and Legal Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of legal authority and judgment in both passages. Pilate''s question about what Jesus has done parallels Gallio''s dismissal of the Jewish case, emphasizing the complexities of legal matters involving religious disputes.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 35, 45, 3, 1, 2, 'Am I a Jew?', 'Jewish Identity and Responsibility', 'This connection highlights the role of the Jewish people in the narrative of Jesus'' trial and the significance of their covenantal relationship with God. Both passages emphasize the Jewish identity and the responsibilities that come with it, particularly in relation to the oracles of God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 36, 42, 17, 20, 21, 'my kingdom is not of this world', 'Nature of the Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize that the kingdom of God is not of this world and cannot be observed externally. Jesus indicates that His kingdom operates on a different plane, highlighting its internal and spiritual nature.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 36, 51, 1, 12, 14, 'my kingdom is not of this world', 'Kingdom of God Connection', 'This connection highlights the nature of Jesus'' kingdom as distinct from worldly powers. Both passages emphasize the concept of being part of a divine kingdom, with Colossians referencing the ''kingdom of his dear Son'' as a fulfillment of Jesus'' declaration.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 36, 45, 14, 17, 17, 'my kingdom is not of this world', 'Nature of the Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the nature of Jesus'' kingdom as distinct from worldly concerns. Both passages emphasize that the kingdom is characterized by spiritual qualities rather than material ones.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 36, 43, 6, 15, 15, 'my kingdom is not of this world', 'Jesus'' Kingdom and Kingship', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' rejection of worldly kingship. In John 18:36, he states that his kingdom is not of this world, while in John 6:15, he departs to avoid being made king by force.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 36, 27, 2, 44, 44, 'my kingdom is not of this world', 'Connection of Kingdoms', 'Both passages emphasize the nature of God''s kingdom. John highlights that Jesus'' kingdom is not of this world, while Daniel prophesies a kingdom that will stand forever, contrasting earthly kingdoms.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 36, 27, 7, 14, 14, 'my kingdom is not of this world', 'Kingdoms of Jesus and Daniel', 'This connection highlights the nature of Jesus'' kingdom as distinct from worldly kingdoms. Both passages emphasize the everlasting dominion and authority of Jesus'' kingdom, contrasting it with temporal powers.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 36, 54, 6, 13, 13, 'My kingdom is not of this world', 'Connection of Kingdom and Confession', 'This connection highlights the nature of Jesus'' kingdom as distinct from worldly powers. Both passages emphasize Jesus'' testimony before authority figures, illustrating His commitment to a divine mission rather than a political one.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 37, 43, 8, 47, 47, 'heareth my voice', 'Hearing and Truth Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of hearing and recognizing truth. In both passages, the ability to hear is linked to one''s relationship with God and truth, emphasizing that those who are of God will recognize His words.', 'theme', 0.482, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 37, 62, 4, 6, 6, 'heareth my voice', 'Connection of Truth and Hearing', 'This connection highlights the theme of truth and the response to it. Both passages emphasize that those who are aligned with God or truth will hear and recognize the voice of Jesus or the apostles.', 'theme', 0.482, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 37, 43, 8, 14, 14, 'bear witness unto the truth', 'Truth and Origin Connection', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' awareness of his origin and purpose. Both passages emphasize the truth of his identity and mission, with Jesus asserting his knowledge of where he came from and his role in bearing witness to the truth.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 37, 62, 3, 19, 19, 'of the truth', 'Connection of Truth in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of truth. In John 18:37, Jesus speaks of bearing witness to the truth, while 1 John 3:19 assures believers that they are of the truth.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 37, 23, 55, 4, 4, 'bear witness unto the truth', 'Witness and Leadership Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus as a witness, as seen in both passages. John 18:37 emphasizes Jesus bearing witness to the truth, while Isaiah 55:4 refers to him as a witness to the people.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 37, 41, 15, 2, 2, 'Art thou a king then?', 'Connection of Kingship Inquiry', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s questioning of Jesus'' kingship. Jesus'' response in both instances indicates an acknowledgment of his identity as king, linking the two moments in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 37, 42, 23, 3, 3, 'Art thou a king then?', 'Connection of Kingship Inquiry', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s inquiry about Jesus'' kingship. The phrase ''Art thou a king'' appears in both, linking their discussions on Jesus'' identity.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 38, 43, 19, 4, 4, 'I find in him no fault at all', 'Pilate''s Declaration of Innocence', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s assertion of Jesus'' innocence. In both instances, he explicitly states, ''I find no fault in him.''', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 38, 42, 23, 4, 4, 'I find in him no fault at all', 'Pilate''s Declaration of Innocence', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s assertion of Jesus'' innocence. In John, Pilate states, ''I find in him no fault at all,'' which is echoed in Luke with ''I find no fault in this man.'' This connection highlights the consistency in Pilate''s judgment across the accounts.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 38, 44, 17, 32, 32, 'What is truth?', 'Truth and Resurrection Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of truth and belief. In John 18:38, Pilate questions the nature of truth, while in Acts 17:32, the response to the resurrection reflects a similar skepticism about truth claims.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 38, 40, 27, 18, 19, 'I find in him no fault at all', 'Judgment and Innocence Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the innocence of Jesus. Pilate declares, ''I find in him no fault at all,'' while his wife warns him about ''that just man.'' This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' unjust treatment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 38, 40, 27, 24, 24, 'I find in him no fault at all', 'Pilate''s Innocence Declaration', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s declaration of innocence regarding Jesus. In John, he states, ''I find in him no fault at all,'' while in Matthew, he asserts, ''I am innocent of the blood of this just person.'' This connection highlights Pilate''s attempts to distance himself from the responsibility of Jesus'' fate.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 38, 41, 15, 14, 14, 'I find in him no fault at all', 'Pilate''s Questioning of Jesus', 'This connection highlights Pilate''s inquiry into Jesus'' innocence in both passages. In John, Pilate states, ''I find in him no fault at all,'' while in Mark, he questions, ''What evil hath he done?''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 38, 42, 23, 14, 16, 'I find in him no fault at all', 'Pilate''s Examination of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s declaration of Jesus'' innocence. In John, Pilate states, ''I find in him no fault at all,'' while in Luke, he similarly asserts, ''I have found no fault in this man.'' This connection highlights the consistent portrayal of Jesus'' lack of guilt across the accounts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 18, 39, 40, 27, 15, 18, 'that I should release unto you one at the passover', 'Release of Prisoners', 'Both passages emphasize the custom of releasing a prisoner during Passover. John 18:39 mentions the release of ''the King of the Jews,'' while Matthew 27:15-18 presents the choice between Barabbas and Jesus. This connection highlights the significance of this custom in the trial of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
